The criteria requires that confirmed Covid cases in countries on the list are similar or below that of the EU's per 100,000 citizens over the previous 14 days (starting from June 15). Countries must also have a "stable or decreasing trend of new cases over this period in comparison to the previous 14 days," while the EU will consider what measures countries are taking, such as contact tracing, and how reliable each nation's data is.

There are currently three requirements to have restrictions listed. First, cases must be stable or decreasing in the last 14 days when compared to the 14 days prior. The US is currently trending downward, though its reporting is hardly stable. Second, countries must have cases per 100,000 close to or lower than the EU average. Right now, the US is at 1,595 while the EU is closer to 20-30. Third, non-tangibles such as testing, tracing, and treatment are taken into account. The US has not yet developed a universal testing and/or tracing plan, and treatments are no more developed than they were several months ago. As such, the US does not qualify for any of the requirements listed, and while they are beginning to decrease national cases, it will be months before they reduce cases enough to hit the second mark and will likely take at least as long to develop the needed non-tangibles to qualify. The only way it happens sooner is if requirements are waived altogether for the US, which is not impossible to remains highly unlikely.

The salient point of the EU’s criteria to allow citizens of third countries to enter the bloc is that the country should have no more than 16 new Covid-19 infections per 100,000 in the previous 14 days. The US is experiencing 1,365 cases per 100,000 as of 31 July 2020 and is still in the first wave of the pandemic. The Spanish Flu pandemic that was between 1918 and 1920 and used as a comparative example experienced four waves. Social distancing and other efforts to contain the virus have been sporadic across the States while easing on the lockdowns has not been consistent and coupled with the lack of a National Health service could exacerbate the transmission of the virus and lengthen the period of infection.
